snippet.textDisplay: Should first watch Ivan Miranda's series on 3D printing a screw drive vehicle. And watch every other video on these sorts of vehicles, which go back to at least the 1920's. Colin has already set his up to fail. The screw cylinders are too small diameter and the driving threads are way too tall, and they're uneven. Look up the old Fordson tractor video and how it easily cruises around in deep snow using large (high flotation) cylinders with a quite shallow thread depth. What ought to work best on Colin's cylinders is wrapping two spirals of steel rod around the cylinders. REDNIC79 built similar vehicle on YouTube back in 2016. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_bHUlJAaE2s

snippet.textDisplay: first I'd'n idea outside my means; I thought who could achieve the feat?  Who'd be super stoked about the reason I had the idea in the first place: I saw a video of an elderly stubborn electric wheelchair bound subject who plowed grudgingly through fresh knee deep power snow, essentially creating a walkway for pedestrians; I'd imagined for him a two-stroke wheelchair-mounted snow-blower. A two-stroke leaf-blower, sheers off the tailings from a two-stroke-auger (same engine?), blowing across a custom auger cowling/ground scraper, & sluice.
